Calculus of Intelligence

1. Core intuition

Intelligence is not a static object.
It is the time-integrated result of repeated local operations under constraint.

A mind, agent, or training process becomes intelligent by:
	•	perceiving state
	•	selecting action
	•	updating under feedback
	•	preserving useful invariants across change
	•	surviving tests that expose false structure

So intelligence is not just what a system can output once.

It is the accumulated ability to maintain coherent adaptation across time, pressure, and domain shift.

