7. Generalization gradient

A real intelligence must transfer beyond one narrow setting.

Let domain set be D = \{d_1, d_2, ..., d_n\}

Let performance in domain d_i be \Pi(d_i)

Define general intelligence gradient as:

G = \frac{1}{n(n-1)} \sum_{i \ne j} \text{Transfer}(d_i \to d_j)

Where Transfer measures how much skill in one domain helps in another.

Then intelligence is not just local competence, but:

I^* = I \cdot G

A system with high local skill but zero transfer has bounded intelligence.
A system with preserved invariants across domains has higher generality.

